The royal privilege gave Lully a very broad monopoly over opera in France.  It

• made every public operatic performance subject to his permission;  
• reserved to him the right to print and sell the librettos of those operas;  
• even limited how many singers and instrumentalists any other troupe could use, so that no one could mount anything approaching an opera without his consent.

What it did ​not​ do was give him a statutory right to pass that monopoly on to his heirs; the privilege was granted at the king’s pleasure and had to be renewed after his death.

